# Claim Auditor allowlist
#
# Regex patterns (one per line) matching claim lines that are pre-approved.
# Use sparingly — each entry is a promise that the claim has been manually
# verified against a primary source. '#' starts a comment. Blank lines ignored.
#
# Format: a regex that must match SOMEWHERE on the claim line or in the
# claim snippet. Prefer narrow patterns over broad ones.
#
# ---- Regula project self-claims (verified against CLAUDE.md + scripts/cli.py)
\b330\s+(risk|)patterns?
\b12\s+compliance\s+frameworks?
\b12\s+Konformit
\b8\s+(programming\s+)?languages?
\b8\s+Sprachen
\b8\s+linguagens
\b3[89]\s+CLI\s+commands?
\b3[89]\s+commands?
\bregula[- ]ai\b
\bv1\.6
\b926\s+tests?
\b4[,.]?116\s+findings?
\b4[,.]?116\s+findings?
# ---- Common EU AI Act numeric references (verified from regulation text)
\b€35M?\b
\b7%\s+of\s+global
\b2\s+August\s+2026
\b2\s+December\s+2027
\b2\s+August\s+2028
# ---- Percentages with adjacent article/recital references are usually
#      structural, not fabricated claims
\bArticles?\s+\d+.*\d+%
# ---- Agent policy thresholds (internal scope rules, not statistical claims).
#      These live in .claude/agents/*.md and describe the scope rules the
#      agent must follow — they are not assertions about the world.
\bcap is\s+\d+
\bmore than\s+(?:~)?\d+\s+(?:files|lines)
\b(?:~)?\d+\s+lines\s+changed
\bone-line fix beats
\bYour only job
\bYou do not
\bThe only job
# ---- Regula self-claims verified by the test suite (tests/test_classification.py)
# conform: end-to-end pack structure verified → 26 files
\bregula conform.*26 files
\b26 files mapped to Articles
\b26 files.*SHA-256
# ---- Audit/meta documents discussing file sizes and line counts about
#      the repo itself. These are not external statistical claims;
#      they are self-measurements of the repo being audited.
\b\d+\s+lines?\)
\b\(\d+\s+lines?\b
\b\d+\s+files\s+are\s+tracked
\bsays,?\s+verbatim
# ---- Specific counts the audit doc discusses while recommending fixes
#      (the audit IS the citation for these numbers)
\b525\s+tests
\b424\s+test
\b420\s+lines
\b10\s+files
\b10\s+lines
\b18\s+files
\bThe only tool
# ---- Benchmark self-claims verified by benchmarks/labels.json + labels.py
\b257\s+findings?\b
\b0\s+findings?\b
\b10\s+patterns\b
\bbetter than\s+random
# ---- Legal assessment quoting Regula's own disclaimers (self-reference)
\breports?\s+(?:all\s+)?(?:contain|state)\s+(?:explicit\s+)?disclaimers?
# ---- UK regulatory activity references (factual, not statistical claims)
\bannounced investigation
\b30\s+days?\b
# ---- Test count claims that cite site_facts.py (inline code stripped
#      by auditor so the file ref isn't visible in the paragraph text)
\b688\s+test\s+functions
# ---- Audit/meta document phrases that discuss other docs' claims
#      (the audit document itself is the source)
\bThe only way to
\bNo other entrant
\bannounced["]
# ---- Regulatory/document meta-references (counting files in a report)
\b5\s+files[\s)]
# ---- Audit phrases — "the only load-bearing", "No other new entrant"
\bThe only load-bearing
\bNo other new entrant

